35 PART II. ADVANCE HEALTH CARE DIRECTIVES
36 SECTION 2.1. G.S. 90-321(c)(3) reads as rewritten:
37 "(3) Except as provided in G.S. 90-321.1, that has been signed by the declarant in
38 the presence of a notary public or two witnesses who believe the declarant to
39 be of sound mind and who state that they (i) are not related within the third
40 degree to the declarant or to the declarant's spouse, (ii) do not know or have a
41 reasonable expectation that they would be entitled to any portion of the estate
42 of the declarant upon the declarant's death under any will of the declarant or
43 codicil thereto then existing or under the Intestate Succession Act as it then
44 provides, (iii) are not the attending physician, licensed health care providers
45 who are paid employees of the attending physician, paid employees of a health
46 facility in which the declarant is a patient, or paid employees of a nursing
47 home or any adult care home in which the declarant resides, and (iv) do not
48 have a claim against any portion of the estate of the declarant at the time of
49 the declaration; andor"
50 SECTION 2.2. G.S. 90-321(a)(1a) reads as rewritten:
House Bill 349-Second Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "(1a) Declaration. – Except as provided in G.S. 90-321.1, any signed, witnessed,
2 dated, and proved signed, witnessed or proved, and dated document meeting
3 the requirements of subsection (c) of this section."
4 SECTION 2.3. G.S. 90-321(d1) reads as rewritten:
5 "(d1) The following form is specifically determined to meet the requirements of subsection
6 (c) of this section:
7
8 ADVANCE DIRECTIVE FOR A NATURAL DEATH ("LIVING WILL")
9
10 NOTE: YOU SHOULD USE THIS DOCUMENT TO GIVE YOUR HEALTH CARE
11 PROVIDERS INSTRUCTIONS TO WITHHOLD OR WITHDRAW
12 LIFE-PROLONGING MEASURES IN CERTAIN SITUATIONS. THERE IS NO LEGAL
13 REQUIREMENT THAT ANYONE EXECUTE A LIVING WILL.
14
15 GENERAL INSTRUCTIONS: You can use this Advance Directive ("Living Will") form to give
16 instructions for the future if you want your health care providers to withhold or withdraw
17 life-prolonging measures in certain situations. You should talk to your doctor about what these
18 terms mean. The Living Will states what choices you would have made for yourself if you were
19 able to communicate. Talk to your family members, friends, and others you trust about your
20 choices. Also, it is a good idea to talk with professionals such as your doctors, clergypersons,
21 and lawyers before you complete and sign this Living Will.
22
23 You do not have to use this form to give those instructions, but if you create your own Advance
24 Directive you need to be very careful to ensure that it is consistent with North Carolina law.
25
26 This Living Will form is intended to be valid in any jurisdiction in which it is presented, but places
27 outside North Carolina may impose requirements that this form does not meet.
28
29 If you want to use this form, you must complete it, sign it, and have your signature witnessed by
30 two qualified witnesses and or proved by a notary public. Follow the instructions about which
31 choices you can initial very carefully. Do not sign this form until two witnesses and or a notary
32 public are present to watch you sign it. You then should consider giving a copy to your primary
33 physician and/or a trusted relative, and should consider filing it with the Advanced Health Care
34 Directive Registry maintained by the North Carolina Secretary of State:
35 http://www.nclifelinks.org/ahcdr/State.
36
37 My Desire for a Natural Death
38
39 I, ____________________, being of sound mind, desire that, as specified below, my life not be
40 prolonged by life-prolonging measures:
41
42 …
43
44 I hereby state that the declarant, ______________________, being of sound mind, signed (or
45 directed another to sign on declarant's behalf) the foregoing Advance Directive for a Natural
46 Death in my presence, and that I am not related to the declarant by blood or marriage, and I would
47 not be entitled to any portion of the estate of the declarant under any existing will or codicil of
48 the declarant or as an heir under the Intestate Succession Act, if the declarant died on this date
49 without a will. I also state that I am not the declarant's attending physician, nor a licensed health
50 care provider who is (1) an employee of the declarant's attending physician, (2) nor an employee
51 of the health facility in which the declarant is a patient, or (3) an employee of a nursing home or
