42 PART III. ELECTRONIC FILING OF HEALTH CARE POWERS OF ATTORNEY AND
43 ADVANCE HEALTH CARE DIRECTIVES WITH THE NORTH CAROLINA
44 SECRETARY OF STATE
45 SECTION 3.1. G.S. 130A-466 reads as rewritten:
46 "§ 130A-466. Filing requirements.
47 (a) A person may submit any of the following documents and the revocations of these
48 documents to the Secretary of State in electronic or hard copy format for filing in the Advance
49 Health Care Directive Registry established pursuant to this Article:
50 (1) A health care power of attorney under Article 3 of Chapter 32A of the General
51 Statutes.
House Bill 349-Second Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) A declaration of a desire for a natural death under Article 23 of Chapter 90 of
2 the General Statutes.
3 (3) An advance instruction for mental health treatment under Part 2 of Article 3
4 of Chapter 122C of the General Statutes.
5 (4) A declaration of an anatomical gift under Part 3A of Article 16 of Chapter
6 130A of the General Statutes.
7 (5) A Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) waiver.
8 (b) Any document and any revocation of a document submitted for filing in the registry
9 shall be notarized regardless of whether notarization is required for its validity. This subsection
10 does not apply to a declaration of an anatomical gift described in subdivision (a)(4) of this
11 section.
12 (c) The document may be submitted for filing only by the person who executed the
13 document.
14 (d) The person who submits the document shall supply a return address.
15 (e) The document shall be accompanied by any fee required by this Article."
16 SECTION 3.2. G.S. 130A-468 reads as rewritten:
17 "§ 130A-468. Filing of documents with the registry.
18 (a) When the Secretary of State receives a hard copy of a document that may be filed
19 with the registry pursuant to this Article, the Secretary shall create a digital reproduction of that
20 document and enter the reproduced document into the registry database. When the Secretary of
21 State receives a document in electronic format that may be filed with the registry pursuant to this
22 Article, the Secretary shall enter that document into the registry database. The Secretary is not
23 required to review a document to ensure that it complies with the particular statutory
24 requirements applicable to the document. Each document entered into the registry database shall
25 be assigned a unique file number and password.
26 (b) Upon entering the a reproduced hard copy of a document into the registry database,
27 the Secretary shall return the original hard copy of the document and a wallet-size card containing
28 the document's file number and password to the person who submitted the document. Upon
29 entering into the registry database a document that was received in electronic format, the
30 Secretary shall send a wallet-size card containing the document's file number and password to
31 the person who submitted the document.
32 (c) When the Secretary of State receives a revocation of a document that is filed with the
33 registry and that document's file number and password, or a request to remove that document
34 from the registry without its revocation, the Secretary shall delete that document from the registry
35 database.
36 (c1) The Secretary of State may remove documents of deceased registrants from the
37 registry upon notification of death in writing in a form acceptable to the Secretary of State.
38 (d) The Secretary of State's entry of a document into, or removal of a document from, the
39 registry database does not do any of the following:
40 (1) Affect the validity of the document in whole or in part.
41 (2) Relate to the accuracy of information contained in the document.
42 (3) Create a presumption regarding the validity of the document, regarding the
43 accuracy of information contained in the document, or that the statutory
44 requirements for the document have been met."
45
46 PART IV. EFFECTIVE DATE
47 SECTION 4.1. This act becomes effective October 1, 2025.
